"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-24","<p>On 19 May 2016, there were a total of 28,420 people waiting to attend a rearranged work capability assessment having had their initial appointment cancelled of which 17,019 have a new appointment already allocated.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-24T13:09:04.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519375/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519375/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519375/answer/previousversion/228","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36280, how many people are waiting for a rearranged work capability assessment having had their initial appointment cancelled.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>Work Capability Assessments can be cancelled for a wide variety of reasons linked to the need for matching the customer’s own requirements with the availability of all those parts necessary for an assessment to take place. Over half of all cancellations are customer instigated cancellations.</p><p> </p><p>Where the cancellations are instigated by DWP we will rearrange the appointment at a convenient time for the customer.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-23T16:53:00.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519376/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36280, for what reasons work capability assessments have been cancelled.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519377","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>My Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions (Stephen Crabb) has replied to the Rt. Hon. Member today.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-23T14:43:01.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519377/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519377/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects to reply to the letter of 1 March 2016 from the Rt hon. Member for Birkenhead on the recommendations made by the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Hunger.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519378","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>Centre for Health and Disability Assessments offer audio recordings to customers who request them in advance, or on the day, and recording machines are now available at every assessment centre. For every 10,000 Work Capability Assessments completed the Department receives an average of 66 requests for an audio recorded assessment.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently 24 audio-recording machines in Scotland and the North East; 43 in North and Central England; 39 in Wales and the West, and; 22 in London and South England, totalling 128 for Great Britain.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>(Source: Centre for Health Disability Assessments)</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-23T16:40:20.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519378/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519378/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many pieces of recording equipment are available in each region of the UK for the purposes of recording work capability assessments.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519380","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Secretary of State is in regular contact with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a range of pensions issues.</p><p> </p><p>The State Pension age changes, which were made to put pensions on a more financially sustainable footing given increases in life expectancy, were fully debated and voted on when the legislation was before Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>During the Pensions Act 2011 a concession, worth £1.1 billion, was introduced to limit the impact of the rising State Pension age on those women most affected. These transitional arrangements capped the maximum delay at 18 months rather than two years, relative to the previous timetable.</p><p> </p><p>Unwinding any of these changes means asking young people to assume more of the cost, and after they’ve already borne their fair share of the tough decisions made last Parliament to bring Government spending under control.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, the Secretary of State is clear that there are no plans to bring forward further concessions or changes.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-26T14:16:19.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519380/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519380/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on potential mitigation measures for women that have witnessed an increase in their pensionable age.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","37193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519381","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>No estimate has been made of the number of people having to travel more than one hour to attend a Jobcentre Plus office in order to obtain a National Insurance number in the last 12 months.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-23T16:40:38.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519381/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519381/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Jobcentres: National Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has made an estimate of the number of people having to travel more than one hour to attend a jobcentre plus office in order to obtain a National Insurance number in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","37202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519382","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>From 2010 to 2013 DWP had 2 specialist National Insurance number (NINo) Centres (Glasgow and Isle of Wight) able to issue NINos .</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, DWP issued NINos from 3 sites (Glasgow, Isle of Wight and Tooting).</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, DWP issued NINos from 5 sites (Glasgow, Isle of Wight, Tooting, Slough and Cambridge)</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, to date, DWP is issuing NINos from 4 sites (Glasgow, Isle of Wight, Tooting and Slough)</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-23T15:02:15.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519382/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519382/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Jobcentres: National Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many jobcentre plus offices have been able to issue National Insurance numbers to new arrivals into the UK in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","37203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519383","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service regularly publish statistics on Personal Independence Payment appeals, which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics</a>. However, these are not broken down by appellants’ main disabling condition and this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that the transition from Disability Living Allowance to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) can be challenging for some individuals, which is why the Department worked closely with Motability as we developed our plans for the introduction of PIP. The Motability charity provides a one-off package of transitional support and advice to support customers who no longer meet the eligibility criteria for the Motability Scheme. For most of these customers who entered into their first lease agreement with Motability before January 2013, Motability will provide transitional support of £2,000. This will enable many former Scheme customers to continue to meet their mobility needs by purchasing a used car.</p><p> </p><p>For customers who entered into their first lease agreement with the scheme during 2013, Motability will supply transitional support of £1,000 to assist with mobility costs. Motability is also providing help with the cost of adaptations made to non-scheme vehicles and information on non-scheme motoring and insurance. The Scheme also offers customers an opportunity to purchase their vehicle after the end of the lease.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-23T11:47:40.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519383/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519383/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Motability: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with Parkinson's disease who were assessed as being ineligible under personal independence payment for a Motability vehicle to which they were entitled under disability living allowance have had that decision overturned at (a) mandatory reconsideration and (b) appeal.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","37206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519384","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-27","<p>The terms of the UK’s bilateral social security agreements with EU Member States, some of which date from the 1950s, are generally superseded by EU Regulations.</p><p>The Government’s position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. If the result of the referendum is a decision to leave, then the Government will have two years under the Article 50 process to seek to negotiate the terms, including the payment of pensions, of the UK’s exit, with the possibility of extending this time frame with the agreement of the other 27 Member States.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-27T13:40:11.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519384/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519384/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","State Retirement Pensions: Uprating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with which other EU countries the UK has a bilateral arrangement for the payment of annual uprating of pensions that would remain in force in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","37274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519385","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Department does not hold the information requested.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-26T15:08:52.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519385/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519385/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on what other OECD member states do not uprate the pensions of its pensioners living abroad; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","37312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519386","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-24","<p>The Pensions Act 2014 provides a statutory framework, which commits future governments to regular and structured review of the State Pension age at least once every six years. The first review, due to report by May 2017 will take into account up to date life expectancy data and the findings of the independently led review.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-24T15:06:07.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519386/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519386/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what account his Department is taking of future levels of healthy life expectancy in making decisions on future levels of pension age.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","37321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519387","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>The State Pension age changes, which were made to put pensions on a more financially sustainable footing given increases in life expectancy, were fully debated and voted on when the legislation was before Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>During the Pensions Act 2011 a concession, worth £1.1 billion, was introduced to limit the impact of the rising State Pension age on those women most affected. These transitional arrangements capped the maximum delay at 18 months rather than two years, relative to the previous timetable.</p><p> </p><p>Unwinding any of these changes means asking young people to assume more of the cost, and after they’ve already borne their fair share of the tough decisions made last Parliament to bring Government spending under control.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, the Secretary of State is clear that there are no plans to bring forward further concessions or changes.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-26T15:04:19.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519387/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519387/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will (a) review and (b) slow down the rate of increase in pensionable age for women.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","37311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519388","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-24","<p>The information you have requested is available in the official Universal Credit statistics: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-24T13:18:35.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519388/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519388/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519388/answer/previousversion/234","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Universal Credit: Blackpool South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants there were in Blackpool South constituency in (a) June 2015, (b) December 2015 and (c) the latest month for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","37492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519389","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-24","<p>Universal Credit live service rolled out to Northampton Jobcentre Plus on 23 November 2015. Official Universal Credit statistics can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Every jobcentre across the country is now delivering Universal Credit for single people. The full Universal Credit service begins its national expansion from May 2016.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-24T13:04:17.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519389/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519389/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Universal Credit: Northampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the progress that has been made in the rollout of universal credit in Northampton.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","37415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519390","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-27","<p>The estimates given in the answer to question 17583 differ from the figures in the Impact Assessment (£123m) because:</p><p> </p><p>i. The actual caseload has been slightly smaller than was forecast at the time of the Impact Assessment and</p><p>ii. There has been improved analysis of the effort required to close cases, informed by the actual experience of closing cases.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-27T14:03:55.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519390/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519390/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 8 December 2015 to Question 17583, on child maintenance, for what reason there is a difference between the estimated costs of (a) caseworker activity to review and update Child Support Agency (CSA) arrears and (b) establishing arrears on the CMS system set out in paragraph 93 of the Department's final impact assessment on CSA case closure, dated 10 April 2013, and those supplied in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","37474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519391","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-27","<p>The 2015 Spending Review agreed funding rising to £130m per year for the Work and Health Programme, focussing support for people with a disability or health condition and the long term unemployed (over 24 months). This figure is separate and in addition to the Prime Minister’s announced plans to provide further support and funding for people with mental health issues to retain or regain employment.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-27T13:52:27.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519391/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519391/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Employment Schemes: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 13 April 2016 to Question 32812, whether the figures provided for sums to be spent annually and in total are additional to each other; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","37473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519392","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>The total number of calls made to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) Claims and Enquiry lines that were unable to access our services due to heavy demand at peak periods including customers receiving a busy or engaged tone are set out below, this covers the period 1 January to 30 April 2016:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Calls Received</p></td><td><p>Calls not Connected</p></td><td><p>% Not connected</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP Claims</p></td><td><p>411,147</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>0.04%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP Enquiries</p></td><td><p>1,113,803</p></td><td><p>18,949</p></td><td><p>1.70%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department employs the following contingency arrangements to reduce the level of unanswered calls::</p><p> </p><ul><li>assigning staff that are undertaking clerical work to take calls for busy periods,</li><li>opening extra hours and ask for staff to volunteer to take additional calls</li><li>postponing non-priority offline time (L+D, team meetings etc.) to meet the demands of the customers</li><li>increasing the amount of open lines before a call is blocked by the network.</li></ul>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-26T14:03:03.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519392/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519392/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on how many occasions has the personal independence payment (PIP) telephone has been unobtainable to the public in 2016; and how many people calling to enquire about PIP have been affected by those incidents.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519393","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>The information requested could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-23T11:54:09.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519393/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519393/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of (a) disability living allowance and (b) personal independence payments have (i) lost or (ii) gained the higher rate mobility allowance since 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ronnie Campbell","Blyth Valley","Mr Ronnie Campbell","37496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519394","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Health and Safety Executive undertook approximately 18,000 targeted inspections in 2015/16, and will seek to maintain current levels of its core regulatory activities, including inspection, each year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-23T13:57:43.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519394/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519394/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many safety inspections the Health and Safety Executive carried out in the last year for which figures are available; and what estimate he has made of the number of such inspections the Executive will be able to make with the planned budget for 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","37427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519395","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) and the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) commissioned a report into age and employment in 2011 <a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/research/rrpdf/rr832.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/research/rrpdf/rr832.pdf</a>. The report found little conclusive evidence that older workers have an increased risk of work related accidents than younger workers. However, if an older worker is involved in a work related accident, the individual is likely to suffer more serious injuries, permanent disabilities or death, than for a younger worker. This is supported by statistics published by HSE.</p><p>The report also found there is little evidence that chronological age is a strong determinant of health, cognitive or physical abilities, sickness absence or productivity.</p><p>HSE’s website includes specific guidance on how to tackle and address health and safety issues in relation to older workers <a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/vulnerable-workers/older-workers.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/vulnerable-workers/older-workers.htm</a>. Additionally, as part of the European Occupational Safety and Health Agency campaign – Healthy workplaces for all ages, HSE is currently working with external stakeholders to specifically target high risk industries with high ratios of older workers, such as agriculture.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-23T10:51:46.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519395/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519395/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Health and Safety Executive has made of the effect of an ageing workforce on safety at work in the UK.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","37424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520960","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-24","The Government believes that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. That way, the UK can play a leading role in one of the world’s largest organisations. Membership of the EU, like our membership of NATO and the UN, amplifies, not diminishes, the UK’s influence in the world.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-24T16:02:41.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520960/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520960/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the UK's influence in the world of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","905061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520961","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-24","<p>As a leading member of the EU, the UK is a major influence on EU external policy and is able to shape the use of the EU’s available policy tools to enhance our security: for example, sanctions policy in respect of Russia and Iran and capacity building support to the states of the Western Balkans. I am in no doubt that Britain’s leading role in this process greatly contributes to the effectiveness of EU policy initiatives and thus maintaining peace and stability in Europe and beyond. All of that would be lost if Britain were to leave the European Union. I am clear that Britain is stronger, safer more prosperous inside the EU than it would be outside.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-24T16:06:15.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520961/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520961/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on peace and stability in Europe and around the world of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","905058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-24","The UK and India have a broad and deep friendship symbolised by Their Royal Highnesses The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge’s visit last month and Prime Minister Modi’s visit to the United Kingdom in November 2015. The UK is the largest G20 investor in India and Indian companies invest more in the UK than the rest of the EU combined.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-05-24T15:17:20.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520962/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","India: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the strength of diplomatic and economic relations between India and the UK.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","905056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520963","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-24","<p>The decision in the forthcoming referendum is one for the British people alone to make. In the nearly 2 years I have been Foreign Secretary, I have visited over 70 different countries in 6 continents – and in no single one of them have I been told that Britain’s influence would be greater if it were not a member of the EU. On the contrary whether in China, in the USA, in Australia, in Nigeria, Britain is seen as more influential because of its membership of the EU. We get two bites of the cherry: Britain’s is a strong and influential voice in its own right; but it is also the voice of a leading Member State of the world’s largest economic block. Membership of the EU does not diminish Britain’s influence; it enhances it – and I speak from personal experience.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-24T15:48:56.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520963/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520963/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the UK's international and diplomatic relations.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","905054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520964","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-24","<p>Foreign Policy is a reserved matter under the terms of the Devolution Settlements. A UK Minister will normally take the chair at Council meetings. In the absence of a UK Minister, arrangements are in place whereby a Minister of a devolved administration may take the Chair, subject to certain conditions. No detailed planning for EU Council meetings during the UK Presidency has yet taken place.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-24T16:22:08.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520964/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520964/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","Agriculture and Fisheries Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, If he will make it his policy that the Scottish Government Minister with responsibility for fisheries will chair meetings of the Agriculture and Fisheries Council when the UK holds the presidency of the Council of the EU in 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","905060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","true","2016-05-24","<p><del class="ministerial">I refer the Honourable Lady to my earlier answer in response to Question 16 (PQ905054.)</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Government believes that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. That way, the UK can play a leading role in one of the world’s largest organisations. Membership of the EU, like our membership of NATO and the UN, amplifies, not diminishes, the UK’s influence in the world.</ins></p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-05-24T15:52:18.66Z","2016-05-26T10:14:53.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520965/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520965/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520965/answer/previousversion/404","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-18","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the UK's influence in the world of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","905057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521418","Wales Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>My office remains in close contact with the Department of Energy and Climate Change on the potential development of a tidal lagoon in Swansea Bay.</p><p> </p><p>We have announced an independent review into tidal power which will be led by industry expert Charles Hendry, who is well regarded across the energy industry and on both sides of the House.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-05-25T14:51:42.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521418/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521418/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-05-18","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the Swansea Bay tidal lagoon project.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","905024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521419","Wales Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>Wales Office Ministers have regular discussions with colleagues in the Ministry of Justice on a range of issues including our plans to reform the UK Human Rights framework.</p><p> </p><p>Revising the Human Rights Act can only be done by the UK Parliament and we will consult fully before bringing forward proposals.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-05-25T14:49:40.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521419/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521419/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-05-18","Human Rights Act 1998: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Justice on the potential effect on Wales of plans to repeal the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","905022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518530","Prime Minister","false","2016-05-12","<p>I was referring to reports that Mr Gani supports an Islamic state. I am clear that this does not mean Mr Gani supports the organisation Daesh and I apologise to him for any misunderstanding.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-05-12T09:03:19.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518530/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518530/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-05-11","Suliman Gani","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if he will clarify his recent remarks concerning Suliman Gani.","false","Biography information for Mr Keith Simpson","Broadland","Mr Keith Simpson","37017"
