"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518085","Department of Health","false","2016-05-12","<p>Figures published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre show that there has not been a reduction in the number of consultant clinical pharmacologists employed in the National Health Service in England.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its workforce planning, Health Education England (HEE) take account of a range of factors including forecast rates of retirement. HEE has recently undertaken a review of the clinical pharmacology and therapeutics workforce, the findings of which will contribute to future workforce planning for this specialty in England.</p><p> </p><p>It is for the respective Governments in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to consider workforce planning for their health system.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL8247 ; HL8248 ; HL8249 ; HL8250 ; HL8251","2016-05-12T10:05:25.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518085/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518085/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-09","Clinical Pharmacologists","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the NHS of the predicted loss of 35 per cent of current clinical pharmacologist consultant posts through retirements in the next decade and the reduction in the number of training grade clinical pharmacologist posts, as set out in the report by the British Pharmacological Society, <i>A Prescription for the NHS: Recognising the value of clinical pharmacology and therapeutics</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL8246"
