"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518100","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office continues to work closely with police forces to ensure that we are best placed to tackle the threat posed by cyber crime.</p><p>Through the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP), we invested over £90 million during the last Parliament to bolster the law enforcement response.</p><p>As the Chancellor announced in November, this Government has committed to spending £1.9 billion on cyber security over the next five years, including for tackling cyber crime.</p><p>The Home Office is also supporting the work led by Chief Constable Stephen Kavanagh, the National Policing Lead for Digital Investigation and Intelligence (DII), to build capabilities to combat the full range of digital crime types. In addition we are providing funding through the Police Transformation Fund to support police led programmes to provide a step-change in digital capability.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL8263","2016-05-12T10:08:14.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518100/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518100/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Police: Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in working with Chief Police Officers to tackle cybercrime.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518101","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The most recently published crime statistics for England and Wales show that in the year ending December 2015 of the 617,618 fraud offences reported to the National Fraud Investigation Bureau, 14,347 (2.3%) were recorded under the Computer Misuse Act (i.e. cyber-dependent offences). This figure represented a 6% decrease compared to the year ending December 2014.</p><p>While overall crime has fallen by more than a quarter since 2010, it is also changing. An accurate national picture is critical to informing our response to cyber crime. That is why the Office for National Statistics have now published, for the first time, initial experimental estimates of the numbers of cyber crimes committed.</p><p>Based on a preliminary field trial, ONS estimate 5.1m fraud incidents and 2.5m incidents of computer misuse crime per year. Following the success of this trial, new questions relating to fraud and cybercrime were introduced onto half the survey sample from October 2015 and will be reported on a quarterly basis from later this year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-12T10:17:42.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518101/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518101/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of cybercrime attacks and their impact on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518102","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Through the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP), we invested over £90 million during the last Parliament to bolster the law enforcement response. As the Chancellor announced in November, this Government has committed to spending £1.9 billion on cyber security over the next five years, including activity to help businesses and individuals protect themselves from cyber crime. The Government is also creating the National Cyber Security Centre, which will open in October 2016, to simplify the current cyber security landscape. This year, we will also publish a second five-year National Cyber Security Strategy which will set out our approach to how we will continue to defend the UK from cyber crime.</p><p>Through the NCSP we are funding the Cyber Streetwise campaign (www.cyberstreetwise.com), which encourages the public and Small and Medium Enterprises to adopt more secure online behaviour. The latest phase of the campaign, launched in September 2015, is focussed on addressing the estimated 80% of cyber crime that could be prevented through the adoption of three simple online behaviours: use three random words to create a strong password; install security software on all devices; and always download the latest software and app updates as soon as they appear.</p><p>We are also clear that banks have a central role in the prevention of fraud and cyber crime. The Home Secretary announced our new Joint Fraud Taskforce on 10 February. The Taskforce is a collaboration of the banks, law enforcement and government, at the most senior levels. Its aim is to protect the public from financial fraud, including cyber-enabled fraud, to reduce the impact of fraud on victims and increase the disruption and prosecution of fraudsters.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-05-12T10:18:25.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518102/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518102/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that businesses and individuals are being adequately protected from the financial impact of cybercrime.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518103","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office continues to work closely with police forces to ensure that we are best placed to tackle the threat posed by cyber crime.</p><p>Through the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP), we invested over £90 million during the last Parliament to bolster the law enforcement response.</p><p>As the Chancellor announced in November, this Government has committed to spending £1.9 billion on cyber security over the next five years, including for tackling cyber crime.</p><p>The Home Office is also supporting the work led by Chief Constable Stephen Kavanagh, the National Policing Lead for Digital Investigation and Intelligence (DII), to build capabilities to combat the full range of digital crime types. In addition we are providing funding through the Police Transformation Fund to support police led programmes to provide a step-change in digital capability.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL8260","2016-05-12T10:08:14.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518103/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518103/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to support research and development to provide continually up-to-date defence against cybercrime.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL8263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518104","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>Central Counterparties (CCPs) play a central role in modern financial markets. As the Prime Minster has made clear, the UK’s new settlement with the EU ensures UK firms, including CCPs, will never face any discrimination for being outside the Eurozone.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the noble Lord also to my written answer of 1 April (HL7153).</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8269","2016-05-12T10:21:47.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518104/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518104/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports that the London Stock Exchange estimates that its acquisition by Deutsche Bourse will lead to a reduction of £7 billion in the margin capital available to protect the financial system from the consequences of counterparty failure, and of whether such a reduction in collateral represents an unacceptable increase in systemic risk.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518105","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Pensions Regulator and the Pension Protection Fund are independent bodies and in carrying out their functions they may meet individuals involved with pension schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers have engaged with a range of sponsoring employers of Defined Benefit pensions schemes as a matter of routine, including Sir Philip Green, as part of their normal considerations of the pensions landscape but oversight of the scheme funding regime for Defined Benefit schemes is a matter for the Pensions Regulator. It would not be appropriate for Ministers to intervene in individual cases or to discuss with the Regulator, the Pension Protection Fund or the scheme sponsor how a particular scheme’s pension deficit should be mitigated.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2016-05-12T10:10:01.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518105/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518105/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","British Home Stores: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they, the Pensions Regulator, or the Pension Protection Fund have in the last three years had discussions with BHS, Lady Green or Sir Philip Green concerning the deficit in the BHS pension fund and a scheme to reduce that deficit.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518106","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>The BHS pension schemes are in Pension Protection Fund (PPF) assessment periods. During this period the schemes are able to accept contributions from the sponsoring employer to cover its debts to the schemes. They are also able to receive recoveries as a creditor or through the use of the Regulator’s powers. If the scheme assets are shown to be sufficient to buy its members annuities at least as good as the compensation paid by the PPF, the scheme will not transfer into the PPF.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2016-05-11T14:45:49.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518106/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518106/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","British Home Stores: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the BHS pension fund has now transferred to the Pension Protection Fund (PPF) or whether the owner, former owner, or secured creditors are still able to make a financial contribution to obviate a need to transfer the fund to the PPF.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518107","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, which includes the credit card sector. Consumer credit regulation transferred from the Office of Fair Trading to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is currently undertaking a thorough review of the credit card market through its ‘credit card market study’. On 3 November 2015 the FCA published its interim report which found that the market was working reasonably well for most customers.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-05-12T10:19:59.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518107/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518107/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Credit Cards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to investigate the growth in the number of banks offering unsecured credit cards with interest and principal payment grace periods of more than three years, in the light of the most recent report by MoneyFacts.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518108","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-11","<p>Her Majesty’s Government has asked the Law Commission to consider the treatment of gift vouchers and pre-payments in the event of retailer insolvency. The Government will consider carefully any recommendations that may emerge on this question once the Law Commission’s report is published in the summer of 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-05-11T11:39:32.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518108/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518108/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-09","Retail Trade: Voucher Schemes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will investigate the case for sales of gift vouchers by retailers to be backed by cash collateral held in independent escrow.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518109","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>Central Counterparties (CCPs) play a central role in modern financial markets. As the Prime Minster has made clear, the UK’s new settlement with the EU ensures UK firms, including CCPs, will never face any discrimination for being outside the Eurozone.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the noble Lord also to my written answer of 1 April (HL7153).</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL8264","2016-05-12T10:21:47.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518109/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518109/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Financial Institutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the presence in the UK of a counterparty clearing house is necessary to the success of the UK as an international financial centre, and whether the presence of such a clearing house is protected by the new settlement for the UK in the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL8269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518110","Department of Health","false","2016-05-12","<p>The evidence and messages in the report of the Academy of Royal Medical Colleges align with the United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ (CMOs) guidelines for physical activity and Public Health England’s physical activity framework ‘Everybody Active Every Day’ both of which highlight the key role of health professionals in promoting physical activity.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to raising awareness of the UK CMOs guidelines and the benefits of physical activity amongst the public and health professionals. The CMO recently launched a new infographic specifically designed to help health professionals to discuss the benefits of physical activity with their patients. The Government also has in place a range of other programmes to support doctors in the promotion of physical activity. These include e-learning modules on physical activity and health, undergraduate training resources for medical, nursing and allied health professionals and Public Health England’s Clinical Champions Programme. Physical activity is also embedded in NHS’s risk reduction services such as NHS Health Checks and the NHS Diabetes Prevention Programme.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-05-12T10:16:17.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518110/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-09","Exercise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the report of the Academy of Royal Medical Colleges in February 2015, <i>Exercise: The miracle cure and the role of the doctor in promoting it</i>, and how that assessment has informed their policy making.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL8270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518112","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2016-05-12","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. I will write directly to my Rt Hon. Friend.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston",,"2016-05-12T12:21:57.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518112/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518112/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2016-05-09","Standing Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House whether she is satisfied with the existing Standing Orders relating to the consideration of primary legislation in its later stages, and if not, whether she will refer that matter to the Procedure Committee.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL8272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518113","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-12","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-05-12T10:58:32.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518113/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518113/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-09","UN Convention for Protection of Cultural Property in Event of Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will introduce legislation to ratify the 1954 Hague Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict and its two Protocols within the next Session.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL8273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518114","Home Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>All information pertaining to the candidates who stood in the 2016 Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC) elections, including details of those elected, is available on the Government website: <a href="http://www.choosemypcc.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.choosemypcc.org.uk</a>.</p><p>In the 2016 PCC elections, 3 independent candidates were elected to the role. In the 2012 PCC elections, 12 independent candidates were elected to the role.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T13:11:19.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518114/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Police and Crime Commissioners: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many independent candidates were successfully elected to the role of Police and Crime Commissioner in 2016, and how that figure compares to the number of independent candidates elected in 2012.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL8274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518115","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>In his speech on 9 May, the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), was clear that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off by remaining a member of the EU. If the UK were to leave the EU, the withdrawal negotiation would need to address a wide range of difficult issues, including co-operation on foreign policy.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-12T10:01:11.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518115/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518115/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-09","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Prime Minister’s comments regarding the stability of peace in Europe if the UK leaves the EU, what contingency plans they have made.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevens of Ludgate",,"Lord Stevens of Ludgate","HL8275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518116","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government believes that the UK should remain in a reformed EU. As the Prime Minister has said, our EU membership helps keep the UK safer and stronger. We have the largest defence budget in the EU and the second largest in NATO. In addition, we have committed to spending 2 per cent of GDP on defence over the course of this Parliament, and the Ministry of Defence's budget will rise by 0.5 per cent above inflation every year to 2020-21. We are maintaining the size of the Army, and we are increasing the size of the Royal Navy, the RAF and the reserves.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-05-12T10:21:18.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518116/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518116/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-09","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Prime Minister’s comments regarding the stability of peace in Europe if the UK leaves the EU, what steps they have taken to strengthen the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevens of Ludgate",,"Lord Stevens of Ludgate","HL8276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518117","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>Senior Civil Servants (SCS) who are moderated as top performers at the end of the performance management year are eligible to receive a bonus payment.</p><p>The performance management year for the SCS runs from 1 April to 31 March. Performance markings for 2015/16 will be determined by the end of May 2016. Only then will the eligibility of SCS for bonus payments be known.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-11T16:42:15.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518117/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518117/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-09","Rural Payments Agency: Performance Related Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Chief Executive Officer of the Rural Payments Agency will receive a bonus payment this year before payments to eligible farmers have been completed.","true","Biography information for Lord Willoughby de Broke",,"Lord Willoughby de Broke","HL8277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518118","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-12","<p>Fly-tipping is unacceptable whether it occurs on public or private land, it spoils our enjoyment of the countryside, can harm human health and wildlife, and damage farming and rural tourism. It also undermines legitimate waste businesses where unscrupulous operators undercut those that operate within the law and is a drain on both local authorities and landowners that clear it up. Tackling this scourge and other forms of illegal waste activity is a priority for the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The exact extent of fly-tipping on private land is unknown as landowners are not required to report this to Defra. However landowner estimates, provided to the Defra chaired National Fly-Tipping Prevention Group, suggest that fly-tipping on private land may cost between £50 million and £150 million per annum in clean up and disposal costs alone.</p><p> </p><p>Some private landowner organisations do report fly-tipping on their land to Defra on a voluntary basis. Between April 2009 and April 2016 these organisation reported some 5,946 fly-tipping incidents on their land. We recognise that the data collected does not fully reflect the scale of the problem.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the inconvenience and costs that fly-tipping poses to landowners and we are working with a wide range of interested parties through the National Fly-Tipping Prevention Group to improve understanding and awareness of the problem as well as sharing best practice about tackling it.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-12T11:39:24.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518118/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518118/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-09","Fly-tipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the levels of fly-tipping on private land across the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL8278"
