"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518161","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The referendum on membership of the European Union is a decision of fundamental importance for the future of the country<strong>. </strong>The Government is committed to helping ensure that everyone who is eligible to vote in this referendum is able to do so.</p><p>The Electoral Commission’s public awareness campaign plays an essential role in explaining to the electorate the importance of registering to vote. As it has done previously ahead of the 2015 General Election, the Government aims to complement and amplify the Electoral Commission’s work to maximise the number of people reached by voter registration communications to ensure that electors can have their say on 23 June. The Government will allocate up to £7.5m for a range of voter registration activity, including funding local authorities and civil society organisations.</p><p>The Electoral Commission and Cabinet Office have been in regular dialogue on encouraging voter registration.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-12T10:17:14.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518161/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518161/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-09","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what (a) the cost to the public purse has been of and (b) advice he has sought or received from the Electoral Commission on Government plans to promote public awareness of the (i) forthcoming EU referendum and (ii) need for timely registration in order to participate in that referendum.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","36782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518162","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Alternative Fuels Framework (AFF) was set out at Pre-Budget Report 2003, and focused on carbon emissions. Based on the evidence available at the time on Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), the AFF found LPG to result in greater natural environmental damage compared to other road fuel gases. It was determined that the environmental case for LPG was poorer than diesel and so its duty differential should be reduce over time.</p><p> </p><p>The government continues to review evidence concerning the environmental impact of LPG and will announce any changes to the tax treatment at fiscal events.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","36852 ; 36853","2016-05-11T16:33:59.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518162/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Petrol Alternatives","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department last conducted a review of the Alternative Fuels Framework.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","36851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518163","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Alternative Fuels Framework (AFF) was set out at Pre-Budget Report 2003, and focused on carbon emissions. Based on the evidence available at the time on Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), the AFF found LPG to result in greater natural environmental damage compared to other road fuel gases. It was determined that the environmental case for LPG was poorer than diesel and so its duty differential should be reduce over time.</p><p> </p><p>The government continues to review evidence concerning the environmental impact of LPG and will announce any changes to the tax treatment at fiscal events.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","36851 ; 36853","2016-05-11T16:33:59.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518163/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518163/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Transport: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which transport emissions are factored into the assessment of fuels within the Alternative Fuels Framework.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","36852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518164","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Alternative Fuels Framework (AFF) was set out at Pre-Budget Report 2003, and focused on carbon emissions. Based on the evidence available at the time on Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), the AFF found LPG to result in greater natural environmental damage compared to other road fuel gases. It was determined that the environmental case for LPG was poorer than diesel and so its duty differential should be reduce over time.</p><p> </p><p>The government continues to review evidence concerning the environmental impact of LPG and will announce any changes to the tax treatment at fiscal events.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","36851 ; 36852","2016-05-11T16:33:59.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518164/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518164/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Liquefied Petroleum Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the latest assessment of liquefied petroleum gas within the Alternative Fuels Framework.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","36853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518165","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs published its latest tax gap estimates on 22 October 2015 in Measuring tax gaps 2015 edition, which is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470540/HMRC-measuring-tax-gaps-2015-1.pdf.</p><p> </p><p>The total tax gap for Income Tax, National Insurance Contributions and Capital Gains Tax for the years from 2009-10 to 2013-14 is set out in Table 1.3 (page 18).</p><p> </p><p>Separate estimates for each of these three components are not available.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-12T07:23:00.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518165/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518165/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the tax gap was for (a) income tax, (b) national insurance contributions and (c) capital gains tax in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518166","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Chancellor announced at Budget 2016 that the soft drinks industry levy will be charged on drinks with added sugar and a total sugar content above 5g/100ml, with a higher charge for drinks with more than 8g/100ml of sugar.</p><p> </p><p>These sugar thresholds provide a strong incentive for companies to reformulate and are set to give industry certainty over the next two years. If companies reformulate their products, as many already have, then they will pay less. But it is up to companies how they respond to the levy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-12T08:02:15.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518166/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518166/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to set target levels of reformulation for soft drinks manufacturers under the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","36826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518167","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>There is no plan to include a time limit in the terms of the soft drinks industry levy, but the Chancellor keeps all taxes under review as part of the Budget process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-12T08:03:08.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518167/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518167/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will include a time limit in the terms of the soft drinks industry levy such that that levy would cease to apply if reformulation targets are met by soft drinks manufacturers.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","36827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518168","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The UK initiated the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) work on country-by-country (CbC) reporting by large multinationals to tax authorities. The UK was one of the first countries to commit to the OECD model of CbC reporting with legislation in Finance Act 2015, and regulations were laid on 26 February 2016 setting the details of implementation in the UK, which apply to accounting periods beginning on or after 1 January 2016. The UK together with 30 countries has signed the OECD Multilateral Competent Authority Agreement (MCAA) to exchange CbC reports.</p><p>The Chancellor has recently pressed the case for public CbC reporting on a multilateral basis. On 12 April 2016 the European Commission published a legislative proposal for public CbC reporting by large multinationals. The UK welcomes this work as a step in the right direction towards new international rules for greater public transparency.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-12T07:22:10.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518168/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518168/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Multinational Companies: Annual Reports","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what timeline he has set for all multinational companies operating in the UK to publish country-by-country reporting; and how that requirement will be enforced.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","36903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518169","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>Statistics on the percentage of gross income paid in direct and indirect taxes by household income quintile are produced as part of the Office for National Statistics publication ‘The Effects of Taxes and Benefits on Household Income’, which can be found here: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/personalandhouseholdfinances/incomeandwealth/bulletins/theeffectsoftaxesandbenefitsonhouseholdincome/2015-06-29" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/personalandhouseholdfinances/incomeandwealth/bulletins/theeffectsoftaxesandbenefitsonhouseholdincome/2015-06-29</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest release shows that in the financial year ending 2014, the top household income quintile paid 24% and 11% of gross income in direct and indirect taxes respectively.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to identify the share of direct and indirect taxes paid by the top 1% of households using this data. However, data on the share of total income tax receipts paid by the top 1% of earners can be found in HM Revenue and Customs’ ‘Income Tax statistics and distributions’ publication, which can be found here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/income-tax-statistics-and-distributions</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-05-12T09:27:20.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518169/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518169/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the proportion of gross income of the top one per cent income bracket which people in that bracket paid in (a) direct and (b) indirect tax in the most recent financial year for which data is available; and what proportion those sums are of gross national income in that same period.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","36884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518170","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government is committed to making sure multinational enterprises pay their share of tax. The UK has been at the forefront of multilateral action through the G20 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) to reform the international tax rules.</p><p> </p><p>We used our Presidency of the G8 in 2013 to successfully initiate the G20-OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) project. The final recommendations were published by the OECD in October 2015, and endorsed by the G20 leaders in November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The BEPS project represents major and unprecedented efforts. The international project involved over 60 countries, including developing countries, to work together on an equal footing to better align the taxation of profits with economic activity and value creation.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has been a leader on implementing the BEPS outputs – we have adopted the OECD country-by-country reporting template; and, at Budget 2016, the UK announced that it would be the first country to act on the OECD recommended rules on interest deductibility.</p><p> </p><p>The UK will continue to participate in international efforts to address BEPS by participating in the OECD’s inclusive framework to monitor implementation, which also involves developing countries, and in work to develop toolkits to assist developing countries implementing the BEPS outcomes.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-12T07:22:33.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518170/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518170/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","Developing Countries: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that UK corporate tax rules do not incentivise companies to avoid tax in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","36905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518171","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-11","<p>The review is expected to be completed and published shortly.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-11T16:14:47.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518171/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518171/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects Louise Casey's review of opportunity and integration in isolated and deprived communities to be (a) completed and (b) published.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","36808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518172","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department records all travel spend under the category of travel and subsistence costs. This is reported in DCLG annual accounts. We are unable to break down the travel and subsistence costs to identify the number of taxi journeys in the last 5 years. This would involve manually analysing individual supplier transactions and could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-05-12T09:21:51.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518172/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518172/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 5 May 2016 to Question 36169, how many taxi journeys his Department paid for in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518173","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-12","<p>Under the voluntary agreement with the National Housing Federation and housing associations, every home sold to tenants will result in an additional affordable home being provided. At least two new affordable homes will be provided for each high value vacant property that is expected to be sold in London. This will lead to an increase in overall housing supply.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-12T09:21:00.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518173/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518173/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Right to Buy Scheme: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of what the likely change in the level of social housing stock will be if the proposed extension of right-to-buy to housing association properties is agreed in (a) Tottenham, (b) Enfield, (c) Haringey, (d) Barnet, (e) Islington and (f) London in (i) 2016 and (ii) each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","36790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518174","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Starter Homes policy is expected to deliver at least a 20% discount from market value on new homes built for first time buyers under 40 years of age. We recognise that first time buyers can face affordability pressures within parts of London which is why we want Starter Homes to make a significant contribution to housing delivery. The London £450k price cap is not an expectation of the going price for a Starter Home. In London in 2014, the average price paid by a first time buyer was £364k – which would equate to a starter homes price of £291k. We are consulting on starter homes regulations which will set the requirement for starter homes and any exemptions. The Department does not make assessments on the number of starter homes that are to be built by local authority area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","36792","2016-05-12T09:06:05.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518174/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518174/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of affordable starter homes that will be built in (a) Tottenham, (b) Islington, (c) Barnet, (d) Haringey, (e) Enfield and (f) London in (i) 2016 and (ii) each of the next four years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","36791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518175","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Starter Homes policy is expected to deliver at least a 20% discount from market value on new homes built for first time buyers under 40 years of age. We recognise that first time buyers can face affordability pressures within parts of London which is why we want Starter Homes to make a significant contribution to housing delivery. The London £450k price cap is not an expectation of the going price for a Starter Home. In London in 2014, the average price paid by a first time buyer was £364k – which would equate to a starter homes price of £291k. We are consulting on starter homes regulations which will set the requirement for starter homes and any exemptions. The Department does not make assessments on the number of starter homes that are to be built by local authority area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","36791","2016-05-12T09:06:05.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518175/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518175/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the average price of affordable starter homes that will be built in (a) Tottenham, (b) Islington, (c) Barnet, (d) Haringey, (e) Enfield and (f) London in (i) 2016 and (ii) each of the next four years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","36792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518176","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-11","<p>The amounts allocated by year for each operational programme for the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) and European Social Fund (ESF) in the UK for the 2014-2020 Multiannual Financial Framework is set out in table 1.6 of the United Kingdom’s Partnership Agreement with the European Commission which can be found on GOV.UK at ‘European Structural and Investment Funds: UK Partnership Agreement’. The table is attached. Each annual allocation needs to be spent within three years.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-11T09:24:45.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518176/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518176/answer","Information from table 1 6_PA - final.doc","ERDF and ESF funding","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518176/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-09","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of (a) regional development funds and (b) structural funds that the UK is due to receive in each year to 2020 under the current EU Multi-Annual Financial Framework.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","36753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518177","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The amount allocated by year to each operational programme for the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) and European Social Fund (ESF) in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland for the 2014-2020 period is set out in table 1.6 of the United Kingdom’s Partnership Agreement with the European Commission, which can be found at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-structural-and-investment-funds-uk-partnership-agreement.</p><p> </p><p>ERDF and ESF allocations beyond the 2014-2020 period will be agreed as part of future European Union Multiannual Financial Framework negotiations.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-11T17:37:03.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518177/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518177/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-09","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount of funding the UK is due to receive in each year to 2030 of (a) regional development funds and (b) structural funds under future EU multi-annual financial frameworks.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","36754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518178","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Government intends to publish its response to the broadband Universal Service Obligation consultation shortly, and a copy will be placed in the House Library.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-12T08:07:25.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518178/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518178/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish responses to the Broadband Universal Service Obligation consultation.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","36781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518179","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-12","<p>In an oral evidence session to the House of Commons Procedure Committee on 27th April it was noted by the Minister for Sport that though the department had experienced a dip in its performance for timeliness of answers to written questions since May 2015, there has also been a significant improvement in performance in recent months.</p><p> </p><p>The Table shows Named Day responses from 27th May 2015 to 29th April 2016:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Minister</p></td><td><p>Named Day Questions answered</p></td><td><p>Number of Late Named Day Questions</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Minister for Culture</p></td><td><p>321</p></td><td><p>146</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Minister for Sport</p></td><td><p>109</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-12T11:32:18.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518179/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518179/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-09","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many and what proportion of named day written parliamentary questions have been answered after the specified date by each Minister in his Department since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518180","Prime Minister","false","2016-05-12","<p>Costs are still being finalised. Details of my speeches are published on the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-05-12T10:20:12.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518180/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518180/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-05-09","Prime Minister: Speeches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what funding from the public purse was allocated to the event at the British Museum which he addressed on 9 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","36855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518181","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Basic Broadband Scheme comprises two schemes running in parallel: the main scheme is administered by the Local Authorities and BT using only satellite suppliers; and the second supplementary scheme is administered by BDUK and uses fixed wireless suppliers as well as satellite suppliers. These schemes form part of the Government's commitment to ensure that every home and business in the UK has access to a broadband service of at least 2 Mbps.</p><p>On the main scheme, there have been 2774 successful applications for codes, with 278 going on to place orders. On the supplementary scheme, there has been 1171 successful applications for codes, with 282 going on to place orders.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-12T11:30:20.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518181/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518181/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many voucher codes have been issued to date under the satellite broadband subsidy scheme; and for what proportion of those codes has installation been completed.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","36864"
