"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518275","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home office publishes statistics on those supported under section 4 at the end of each quarter in the quarterly Immigration Statistics release.</p><p>Of the 3,821 main applicants and dependants that were supported under section 4 as at the end of December 2015, 1,948 were single adults. Where the gender of the main applicant is recorded, 1,544 of these were males and 335 were females.</p><p>The data relating to single adults is a subset of figures published in Table as_18_q, in volume 4 of the latest Immigration Statistics release, available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T11:01:24.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518275/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518275/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) single adult males and (b) single adult females were in reciept of support under the provisions of section 4 of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518276","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Resourcing is an operational matter for individual Chief Constables. We have prioritised child sexual abuse as a national threat in the Strategic Policing Requirement to empower police forces to maximise specialist skills and expertise to prevent offending and resolve cases. This means that police forces must have in place the capabilities they need to protect children from sexual abuse.</p><p>In 2015/16 the Government provided an additional £10 million to the National Crime Agency to create specialist teams to tackle online child sexual exploitation. We have also made available £1.7 million to fund Operation Hydrant, which coordinates the handling of multiple non-recent child sexual abuse investigations specifically concerning institutions or persons of public prominence, and up to £1.5 million to support regional coordinators and analysts to oversee the implementation of the National Policing Plan for tackling child sexual exploitation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-12T09:24:13.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518276/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518276/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the (a) extra cost to police forces and (b) extra staff hours in police forces resulting from the change in the level of reported cases of contact child sex offences in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","36786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518277","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The number of full time equivalent police officers employed in traffic policing roles as at 31 March in each of the last 5 years is provided in the tables. Officers with multiple responsibilities are recorded under their primary function or role. Data for 31 March 2015 (the latest period for which figures are available) can also be found in the supplementary tables of the July 2015 police workforce statistics publication:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/444537/police-workforce-supptabs-mar15.ods</p><p>Reclassification of roles within a force can lead to fluctuations in the number of officers in a particular role.</p><p>As HMIC has made clear, there is no simple link between police numbers and crime levels, between numbers and the visibility of police in the community, or between numbers and the quality of service provided.</p><p>Decisions on the size and composition of the police workforce are operational matters for Chief Officers working with their Police and Crime Commissioners and taking into account local priorities. What matters is how officers are deployed, not how many of them there are.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-12T09:20:38.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518277/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518277/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many traffic police officers were employed in each police force area in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","36785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518278","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>A full Impact Assessment, setting out the cost across Criminal Justice System of the proposed bail reforms, was drawn up as part of the consultation process in late 2014 and was updated in the light of that consultation in March 2015. The Impact Assessment was updated again and published with the Policing and Crime Bill in February 2016; a copy of the latest version is available online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/499365/Impact_Assessment_-_Reform_Pre-Charge_Bail.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/499365/Impact_Assessment_-_Reform_Pre-Charge_Bail.pdf</a></p><p>The Home Office and the Ministry of Justice have worked together closely in drawing up these proposals; I am of course a Minister in both Departments, and my Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Justice is one of the backers of the Policing and Crime Bill.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-12T09:35:54.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518278/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518278/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has had discussions with the Secretary of State for Justice on the potential implications of the proposals in the Policing and Crime Bill to put a limit of 28 days on pre-charge bail for the resources required for bail extension hearings.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","36787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518279","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>We are currently updating our September 2015 country information and guidance on handling asylum claims made by Eritrean nationals.</p><p>The revised guidance will be based on an assessment of a range of sources including the Foreign Office’s Human Rights and Democracy Report 2015 as well as recent publications by Amnesty International and the findings of a Home Office fact finding mission to Eritrea undertaken in February 2016.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T09:46:21.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518279/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518279/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518279/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Asylum: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the findings of the Government's Human Rights and Democracy Report 2015, published on 21 April 2016, on her Department's country guidance on people from Eritrea seeking asylum in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","36796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518280","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>As at 31 December 2015, there were 20 Eritrean nationals in detention in the UK. The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of persons removed or departed voluntarily from the UK within Immigration Statistics. Information on those in detention by nationality is available in the latest release, Immigration Statistics: October to December 2015, table dt_13_q from GOV.UK on the statistics web pages at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:38:16.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518280/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518280/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Detainees: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from Eritrea are currently held in immigration detention centres in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","36797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518281","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Our records indicate that fewer than a total of 5 adults from Eritrea who previously applied for asylum as unaccompanied children were served with removal directions from 2013 to 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:24:28.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518281/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518281/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Deportation: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many adults from Eritrea who previously applied for asylum as unaccompanied children were served with removal directions in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","36798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518282","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>All unaccompanied asylum seeking children, including those from Eritrea, are provided with an interpreter where necessary, access to legal advice, and are referred to the Refugee Council children’s panel.</p><p>Unaccompanied asylum seeking children are placed in the care of local authority children’s services and have access to the same support as all other looked after children.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:53:43.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518282/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518282/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518282/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Asylum: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what (a) translation services and (b) other specialist provisions the Government provides to unaccompanied asylum seeking children from Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","36799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518283","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>I refer my Rt. hon. Friend to the answer given to Question 31328.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:27:00.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518283/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518283/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Immigration Controls: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people carrying passports from other EU member states were refused entry to the UK in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","36783"
