"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518286","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The data requested is not available centrally and is not routinely collected. It could be provided only by examining individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:43:48.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518286/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518286/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 35126, on deportation, how many removals were cancelled after an assessment by a medical escorting officer in 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","36841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518287","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>It is longstanding policy not to disclose details of records which may be held in relation to individuals’ arrival in the United Kingdom as to do so would not be in the interests of national security.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:32:24.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518287/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518287/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people on the Warnings Index her Department knows to have entered the UK since 6 May 2010.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518288","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Data on passengers initially refused entry to the UK were not collected by the Home Office prior to 2004.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T09:42:16.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518288/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518288/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36490, for what reason information on the number of (a) EU and (b) non-EU nationals refused entry to the UK in each year prior to 2004 is not available.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","36873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518289","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>For reasons of national security we do not comment on operational issues relating to border security systems.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:23:10.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518289/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518289/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518289/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Borders: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many times the Semaphore eBorders system has been affected by a national power outage since 6 May 2010; and when each of those power outages (a) started and (b) ended.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518290","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The information published in the quarterly Immigration Statistics is kept under review, taking into account the needs of users, burdens on suppliers and producers, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. There are currently no plans to publish data relating to asylum support statistics by gender.</p><p>Statistics on asylum seekers in receipt of Section 95, Section 4 or Section 98 support are available in Tables as_16_q, as_17_q and as_18_q of the quarterly Immigration Statistics release, available here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:58:29.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518290/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518290/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to publish asylum support statistics by gender as part of the Government's quarterly immigration statistics.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518291","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>I am currently considering a submission from the Orgreave Truth and Justice Campaign containing their extensive and detailed arguments for establishing a public inquiry into the events at Orgreave and will set out the Government’s position in the near future.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-05-12T11:39:53.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518291/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518291/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Orgreave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of a public inquiry related to the miners' strike and events at Orgreave in 1984.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","36836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518292","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office publishes statistics on those supported under section 95, as at the end of each quarter, in the quarterly Immigration Statistics release.</p><p>Of the 34,363 main applicants that were supported under section 95 as at the end of December 2015, 12,561 were single adults. Where the gender of the main applicant is recorded, 9,987 were males and 2,135 were females.</p><p>There were 6,456 families supported under section 95 as at the end of December 2015. It is not possible to identify single parent families from the published statistics.</p><p>The figures provided are published in table as_17_q, in volume 4 of the Immigration Statistics asylum data tables. The data provided by gender are a subset of published figures. The latest release, Immigration Statistics September to December 2015, is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T11:04:15.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518292/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518292/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) single adult men, (b) single adult women, (c) families and (d) single-parent families were in receipt of support under section 95 of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 at the end of 2015.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518293","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Secretary will consider the Home Affairs Committee’s report on their planned inquiry into asylum accommodation when it is published.</p><p>The timing of any decision to extend the COMPASS contracts is subject to ongoing discussions with providers and is commercially sensitive. In deciding whether to extend the contract the Home Office will take a number of things into account, including the performance of the contracts and the value for money that they offer to the taxpayer.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T11:09:15.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518293/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518293/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to consider the final report of the Home Affairs Committee's planned inquiry into asylum accommodation before she makes her decision on whether to extend Compass asylum accommodation to 2019.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518294","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Home Office systems are used for the purposes of border and national security and the detection and prevention of crime. It is longstanding policy not to discuss the specific data held on these systems, the source of the data or how it is used for national security reasons.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:26:10.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518294/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518294/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Borders: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, who on the Government's warnings index is known to have travelled to which destinations during the Semaphore eBorders system national power outage in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","36830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518295","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>In 2014, UK Visas &amp; Immigration in Jordan became aware of potential abuse of the Family Reunion route by individuals claiming to be the dependants of someone granted refugee status in the UK as a Kuwaiti Bidoon. Investigations commenced at this time.</p><p>UK Visas &amp; Immigration has concluded the majority of the applications referenced in the response to Question 21679 and continues to work through those applications that have not yet been concluded.</p><p>UK Visas &amp; Immigration aims to resolve all applications for UK entry clearance within published customer service standards. Where there is a problem with an individual application or if it is complex, UK Visas &amp; Immigration write to the affected applicant to explain why the application will not be decided within the normal standard. All outstanding applications for UK entry clearance from family members of individuals granted refugee status as a Kuwaiti Bidoon which have not been concluded within published customer service standards are currently being prioritised.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T09:29:34.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518295/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518295/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-09","Immigration: Kuwait","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2016 to Question 21679, when her Department's investigations into applications for family reunion from Kuwaiti Bidoon people were initiated; when she expects those investigations to be concluded; whether there is a maximum length of time for which a decision will not be taken on the outstanding applications in that cohort; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","36839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518296","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-05-12","<p>The House is currently completing a procurement process to replace the software system which enables publication of information on the annunciator service. The solution has been specified in such a way that the data will be available in an open format. The information will be published in real time and made available to connected devices.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-05-12T10:55:15.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518296/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518296/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-05-09","House of Commons Annunciator System: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, if the Commission will make information on the House of Commons annunciator available online in real time.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","36829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518297","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The UK is committed to ensuring access to low cost, effective medicines in the developing world, providing a range of significant inputs to increasing access to essential medicines.</p><p> </p><p>We support the provision of essential medicines and other health products through innovative global partnerships such as the Global Fund for AIDS, TB and Malaria (GFATM), UNITAID, GAVI and the Medicines Patent Pool (MPP). We work to strengthen systems weaknesses, such as weak supply chains or poor procurement, which deter private investment, keep medicines prices high or lead to misuse or waste of medicines. We also place a great emphasis on research and development of new vaccines, medicines and diagnostics for conditions that affect millions of poor people. A new £1 billion fund – the Ross Fund - was recently announced with the aim of developing, testing and delivering a range of new products to help combat the world’s most serious diseases, such as malaria, Ebola and TB in developing countries.</p><p>Tackling Antimicrobial Resistance is a key priority for this Government. We are awaiting the final report of the O’Neill Independent Review on Antimicrobial Resistance later this month and the Department of Health will then lead a cross-Government response.</p><p>We support the aims of the UN High Level Panel on Access to Medicines. For it to fulfil its potential to improve access to affordable and quality medicines, including antibiotics, it will need to take a balanced approach, building on the WHO Global Strategy and Plan of Action and engaging with existing global partnerships, and use its influence to galvanise Member States, public and private sectors around a common approach to this important issue.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-05-11T17:00:31.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518297/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518297/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Developing Countries: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to support the work of the UN High Level Panel on Access to Medicines; with reference to the Prime Minister's comments on the pharmaceutical industry to the BBC on 2 July 2014, what recent assessment she has made of the steps to take to resolve market failure related to the development of new classes of antibiotics in that industry; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","36813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518298","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department does not have record of receiving a letter from the hon. Member for Aberdeen North dated 1 December 2015. My office has been in contact with the hon. Member’s office to receive a copy of the letter and we will respond in due course.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-05-12T08:28:41.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518298/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518298/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Aberdeen North of 1 December 2015, on foreign aid.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","36828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518299","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-12","<p>Following confirmation of undisclosed state-guaranteed loans, the UK immediately suspended all direct aid to the Government of Mozambique. This has since been followed by other donors. The UK is working with international partners to assess the implications for programming. The UK’s priority is to continue to support the people of Mozambique to exit poverty and build a more prosperous and secure country.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-05-12T11:28:15.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518299/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518299/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Mozambique: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which projects her Department plans to close following its decision to suspend financial aid payments to the government of Mozambique.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","36892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518300","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-12","<p>A stable, secure and prosperous Ethiopia is critical to millions of poor Ethiopians and the UK’s national interest. UK support to Ethiopia, since 2010, has, for example, helped reduce poverty and child mortality by a quarter. Despite Ethiopia’s remarkable progress against the Millennium Development Goals, we have concerns about their progress on civil and political rights. The UK’s aid relationship with any government is based on an assessment of commitment to our partnership principles, including to human rights and international obligations.</p><p>DFID has supported Ethiopian civil society organisations to respond to the development priorities of poor people and to hold Government to account. In 2015-16 we have developed the capacity of institutions central to upholding accountability including; the Ethiopian Human Rights Commission, the Ethiopian Revenue and Customs Authority, the Office of the Federal Auditor General and the Federal Ethics and Anti-Corruption Commission.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-05-12T08:28:00.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518300/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518300/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Ethiopia: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, in what ways Government aid to Ethiopia assisted in improving democracy and human rights in that country in 2015-16; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","36779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518301","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>In line with UK government commitments to increase transparency, DFID publishes details on our spend, including data on expenses, travel and hotel costs on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development/about/statistics" target="_blank">GOV.UK.</a> Publication includes all spend which, in compliance with HM Treasury guidance, does not compromise national or personal security, foreign relations or legal obligations under acts such as the Data Protection Act.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T16:28:10.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518301/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518301/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Department for International Development: Hotels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of hotel bookings her Department made for its (a) Ministers, (b) special advisers and (c) officials in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518302","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>The top priority for the present has to be ending the conflict and ensuring aid can reach those in need. We are focused on supporting the UN-led peace talks, increasing commercial imports of food, fuel and medical supplies, and improving humanitarian access.</p><p>We will monitor progress against the 2016 UN appeal closely and consider whether a conference is helpful later this year.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T16:27:28.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518302/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518302/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has plans to hold an international donor conference for the humanitarian response in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518303","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>UK aid to Yemen is currently focused on the most urgent life-saving needs, in particular food, nutrition, health, water and sanitation. We have so far helped more than 1.3 million Yemenis who have been affected by the conflict.</p><p>DFID has supported education in Yemen through the Social Fund for Development (SFD). Since 2010, more than 240,000 children have attended schools supported by SFD. DFID is also supporting the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to rehabilitate schools which is helping 3,500 refugee children and Yemeni children from their host communities, to resume education.</p><p>The UK is working closely with the Government of Yemen, Gulf countries, the World Bank, UN and other donors on planning for stabilisation and post-conflict recovery. Any future support will be based upon a comprehensive assessment of needs.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T16:27:55.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518303/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518303/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure emergency education, in particular for displaced children, is prioritised as part of the emergency response in Yemen; and whether education will be prioritised in her Department's support for the recovery and reconstruction of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518304","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>All organisations that DFID contracts with are subject to the standard DFID Terms and Conditions. These are clear on the organisations responsibility for establishing specific country tax obligations and payment requirements. Supplier compliance expectation is reinforced through DFID’s Statement of Priorities and Expectations (SOPE) which specifies the Department’s position regarding tax avoidance.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T16:27:10.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518304/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518304/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-09","Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government takes to ensure that all companies which receive support from her Department are committed to responsible tax behaviour.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","36879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518305","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>IPP prisoners are released where the Parole Board is satisfied that they can be safely managed in the community.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","36765","2016-05-11T16:06:25.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518305/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518305/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-09","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will bring forward regulations to allow re-sentencing of people serving imprisonment for public protection sentences on defined principles specially enacted by Parliament.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","36764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518306","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>IPP prisoners are released where the Parole Board is satisfied that they can be safely managed in the community.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","36764","2016-05-11T16:06:25.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518306/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518306/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-09","Parole","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make plans to use the statutory powers granted to him by section 128 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 to reform the Parole Board release test.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","36765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518307","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>When assessing an offender’s continuing risk for the purposes of deciding whether he or she is eligible for possible release, the independent Parole Board already takes into account any wilful failure on the part of the offender to disclose the whereabouts of their victim’s body. The Parole Board has at my request, agreed to review its guidance on this particular issue as part of a review of all its guidance in 2016.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-05-11T13:46:01.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518307/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518307/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-09","Prisoners' Release: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects the Parole Board to complete its review of the rules on releasing convicted murderers from prison if they refuse to reveal the locations of their victims' bodies.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","36743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518308","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-12","<p>Government data indicates that claims volumes remain at historically high levels. Over a similar period data from the Department for Transport shows accident rates have fallen by around 25%. This is clear evidence that the system is in need of further reform, which is why on 25 November 2015, in his Autumn Statement, the Chancellor announced new measures to reduce the cost and number of whiplash claims. The Government will consult on the detail of these reforms in due course and the consultation document will be accompanied by an impact assessment.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-05-12T09:02:27.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518308/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518308/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-09","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answers of 5 and 12 January 2016 to Questions 20499 and 20722, what assessment his Department has made of the relationship between trends in the levels of motor accident rates and claims payments since 2006.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","36844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518309","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Infrastructure and Projects Authority’s (IPA’s) support to the HS2 Programme is part of the normal assurance process for projects of this size, as mandated by Ministers. The Cabinet Secretary’s involvement is also normal for projects on the scale of HS2.</p><p> </p><p>The IPA’s role on the Government's Major Projects Portfolio is to provide expertise in infrastructure and the financing, delivery and assurance of major projects, to support more effective management and delivery across government. The cross government assurance involves relevant experts from the Infrastructure and Projects Authority, the Department for Transport, HM Treasury and HS2 Ltd.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-12T07:50:58.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518309/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518309/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36401, whether the Cabinet Secretary's involvement in the Infrastructure and Projects Authority's review of High Speed 2 was requested or authorised by a Minister; and what the membership is of the small cross-government team referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518310","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The partnership are contracted to provide advice to the Department on all rail franchises in relation to the Secretary of State’s duties under Section 30 of the Railways Act 1993.</p><p> </p><p>The partnership is also currently advising the Department on a mobilisation plan for the Cross Country franchise. This plan is being prepared on a contingency basis which will be implemented in the event that negotiations on a Direct Award to the current operator fail to reach a successful commercial conclusion.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-12T07:47:21.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518310/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518310/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23836, on railways: franchises, on which franchises the partnership referred to in that Answer has provided advice to him in relation to his duties under Section 30 of the Railways Act 1993; and whether his Department has carried out mobilisation work on any franchises under Section 30 since the contract referred to in that Answer was signed.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518311","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>No specific amount has been allocated to dealing with salt and subsidence issues beyond the funding envelope announced for the project in November 2015.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:07:24.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518311/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518311/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35399, what amount has been allocated within the overall cost envelope to deal with salt and subsidence issues related to the proposed High Speed 2(b) route; and what steps his Department has taken to ensure that that funding is sufficient in the absence of the information that would have been provided by intrusive geological surveys.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518312","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>Virgin Trains East Coast (VTEC) currently provide free wifi to Standard Class passengers for at least the first 15 minutes of use. They also provide free wifi to Standard Anytime ticket holders who have purchased their tickets through corporate sales channels. By end of October 2016, VTEC will provide free wifi to all customers who book through the Franchise Operator's website. VTEC are currently in negotiations with suppliers to provide free wifi by end of 2016 at all VTEC managed stations.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-12T07:17:27.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518312/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518312/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","East Coast Railway Line: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the InterCity  East Coast franchisee expects to introduce free WiFi for standard class passengers on trains on routes under that franchise.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518313","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The final number for 2015/16 is yet to be audited. The official number is due to be published by the Office of Rail and Road on 25th August 2016.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-12T07:27:20.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518313/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518313/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","East Coast Railway Line: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what premium payments were made by the InterCity East Coast franchisee to his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518314","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>Much of the research on the impacts of HS2 on specific areas of the UK so far has focussed on the HS2 named cities such as Manchester, Leeds, Birmingham and London. However, to build an understanding of the potential for HS2 to contribute to balanced economic growth in the UK, <em>The Economic Case for HS2,</em> published in 2013, apportioned the estimated social benefits of the project to different regions. The West Midlands was estimated to receive 15% of the benefit of the full ‘Y’ network in 2036, valued at £303m (in 2011 prices). Coventry, located close to the planned HS2 Birmingham Interchange station, can be expected to benefit from faster journey times through the high speed network as well as released capacity on the classic network.</p><p> </p><p>Early research published in the HS2 <em>Regional Economic Impacts</em> report in 2013 attempted to estimate the gross GVA effects of HS2 on the West Midlands economy in 2037 and produced an illustrative estimate of between £1.5bn and £3.1bn of additional output per annum (in 2013 prices). We continue to refine the methodology of how we assess regional economic impacts and build evidence on the contribution which HS2 could make to creating sustainable and balanced economic growth.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-12T07:14:21.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518314/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518314/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential economic effect of the High Speed 2 project on Coventry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518315","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>Under the Government’s commitment to transparency, the data that is recorded by departments for projects such as HS2 in its Major Projects Portfolio is published by departments alongside the publication of the Annual Report of the Infrastructure &amp; Projects Authority. This data includes financial statistics such as whole life costs of each project as well as total in-year budget, forecast spend and variance. This information is available from GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2009/10 the Government has spent £1.4bn on the HS2 programme. This includes the costs incurred by HS2 Ltd and Land &amp; Property expenditure. In relation to (a), (b) and (c), as of March 2016, £434.4m has been spent on land and property with a further £11.2m in compensation payments associated with the statutory blight regime. Please note that 2015/16 figures have not been audited yet.</p><p> </p><p>With regards to (d), the information on HS2 Ltd salaries is published in the company’s Annual Accounts, which are available from Gov.UK. As of March 2016, the total salaries for HS2 Ltd stand at £80.4m.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T16:14:21.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518315/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518315/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish the total expenditure by HS2 to date; and how much has been spent on (a) land, (b) property, (c) compensation and (d) salaries.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","36747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518318","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department for Transport allocated £20 million of the £80 million Access Fund to a transition year between 2016 and 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The primary objectives of the Sustainable Travel Transition Year remain as per the Local Sustainable Transport Fund to support the local economy; reduce carbon emissions; improve access to jobs, training and education; and increase levels of people cycling and walking. The competition for this was held on 15th February and closed on the 29th March 2016. The competition has now been assessed and the winning bids will be announced shortly.</p><p> </p><p>This transition year has been set up to support local councils in the switch from the Local Sustainable Transport Fund to the Access Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The launch of the £60 million Access Fund will take place later this summer 2016, to provide further support for sustainable and accessible travel projects. Improving access to employment, education and services and improving walking and cycling uptake will be the core objectives.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T10:30:43.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518318/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518318/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Transport: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how he will ensure the Government's £80 million five-year Access Fund will be spent on sustainable transport projects.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","36766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518319","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department for Transport currently provides Best Practice Guidance to assist with the fit and proper person test, which is the responsibility of local authorities.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-11T12:27:30.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518319/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518319/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to define the term, fit and proper, for the licensing of taxi and private hire vehicle drivers.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","36767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518320","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The information requested is provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-12T10:45:36.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518320/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518320/answer","036788 - Breakdown of statutory blight regime and HS2 discretionary scheme payments by parliamentary constituency.xlsx","036788 - Breakdown in Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518320/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 3 May 2016 to Question 35371, if he will provide a breakdown of statutory blight regime and HS2 discretionary scheme payments by parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","36788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518321","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>All survey and study information will be published in due course and it would not be appropriate to publish partial information at this time as this could be misleading to the public.</p><p> </p><p>All meetings with individual business are treated in confidence due to commercial sensitivities surrounding the discussions.</p><p> </p><p>The details of the consultant are treated as commercial in confidence. The consultant was commissioned in January 2014 to undertake this study.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:27:31.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518321/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518321/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35404, if he will place in the Library copies of (a) the High Speed 2 LiDAR surveys, (b) all notes of all the consultations with (i) Tata Chemicals Europe Ltd, (ii) Compass Minerals UK Ltd and (iii) all other brine and salt extraction stakeholders and (c) the details of the mining engineer commissioned to undertake a study of the saltfield including the location of known brine wells; and on what date that study of the saltfield was commissioned.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518322","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>All survey information will be published in due course and it would not be appropriate to publish partial information at this time as this could be misleading to the public.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:12:35.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518322/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518322/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35453, if he will place in the Library a copy of the surveys referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518323","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>I last met with representatives from across the insurance industry on 14 January to discuss a range of issues. These included young driver safety and technology measures which can reduce the cost of insurance and thus reduce incentives to drive without insurance and the implications of a European Court of Justice Judgment on the scope of compulsory motor insurance. In addition I met with the British Insurance Brokers’ Association last summer, shortly after my appointment.</p><p> </p><p>My officials have regular meetings with representatives from the insurance industry. At these a range of issues have been discussed including young driver safety and technology such as telematics, uninsured driving, the scope of compulsory motor insurance, and driverless cars. Representatives of some parts of that industry have raised with us the issue of Insurance Premium Tax; this is a matter for the Chancellor of the Exchequer.</p><p> </p><p>There have been no recent meetings with personal injury law firms regarding motor insurance.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-12T08:07:14.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518323/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518323/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 34946, what the recent meetings held by Ministers and officials of his Department with the motor insurance industry were that were referred to in that Answer and what was discussed at those meetings; and how many meetings he has held with personal injury law firms in the same time period and what was discussed at those meetings.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518324","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>HS2 will negotiate access to land with landowners to undertake geological surveys as a part of the Hybrid Bill process following the decision of the route as done on Phase 1 and Phase 2a. It would not be appropriate to intrude on landowners where there is no confirmation of the route.</p><p> </p><p>Both the study and the re-review will be used to support technical decisions contributing to a route announcement scheduled for later in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:21:36.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518324/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518324/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35403, on High Speed 2 railway line: Eddisbury, for what reasons no intrusive geological surveys have been carried out at this stage; when HS2 Ltd commissioned from a mining engineer, in consultation with the Cheshire Brine Subsidence Compensation Board, a study of the historical subsidence effects and ongoing extractive processes in relation to salt; on what date HS2 Ltd received or will receive that report; and when he expects to receive the conclusions of the re-review of the usefulness of satellite interferometry to evaluate historical ground movement across Cheshire.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518325","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>The fishing vessel <em>Louisa</em> sank off the Scottish coast on 9 April 2016. The Marine Accident Investigation Branch (MAIB) is seeking to raise the vessel as part of its investigation to establish the causes and circumstances of the accident.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s procurement experts have independently reviewed the processes undertaken by the MAIB in awarding the contract to recover the <em>Louisa</em>. It is clear from that review that the MAIB’s evaluation team followed the process as set out in the tender document and in a fair and transparent manner. I am therefore satisfied that there are no grounds for the procurement process to be suspended.</p><p> </p><p>This sinking resulted in the deaths of three fishermen and the vessel should be recovered as soon as possible to give the investigation team the strongest possibility of understanding the reasons why this tragic accident occurred.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-12T08:14:03.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518325/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518325/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Wrecks: Hebrides","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will suspend the procurement exercise for the recovery of the FV Louisa pending investigation of the tendering process for that recovery.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","36897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518326","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>HS2 will undertake a more detailed assessment of environmental impacts as a part of the Hybrid Bill process following the decision of the route as done on Phase 1 and Phase 2a. It would not be appropriate to undertake detailed studies where there is no confirmation of the route.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:41:22.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518326/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518326/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35400, for what reasons HS2 Ltd has not undertaken any work other than desktop studies in relation to the potential effect on aquifers, canal routes, roads and other surface obstacles in respect of Phase 2b of the route.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518327","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>As set out in my previous answer, HS2 Ltd and the Department for Transport have been analysing options across the route following the consultation. It would not be appropriate to go into detail on any individual location before a route decision has been taken. A route decision is planned for autumn 2016.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-11T09:37:13.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518327/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518327/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35238, whether any factors relevant to (a) Cheshire and (b) Eddisbury have had a bearing on delays in announcing the route of Phase 2b of High Speed 2 from Crewe to Manchester.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","36911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518328","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department does not have this information. We understand the Office of Rail and Road intends to publish the results of this work, alongside its first annual report on consumers titled ‘Measuring Up’, shortly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-11T15:48:41.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518328/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518328/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Railways: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Office of Rail and Road super-complaint response report, published in March 2016, paragraph 207, which three train operating companies scored 0 per cent for their sampled mystery shops.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","36929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518329","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>Post Office Card Accounts provide a useful service to many people and there are no plans to change provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises, however, that working age claimants may also be receiving wages. As the account does not receive wages or allow for direct debit or standing order facilities, Post Office Card Accounts are not suitable for all of their needs. Those claimants are therefore being encouraged to open main stream bank accounts including credit union accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The Post Office Card Account contract was awarded from 01 December 2014 and expires on 30 November 2021 and there are no plans to amend that term.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","36899 ; 36901","2016-05-12T07:26:50.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518329/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518329/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Post Office Card Account","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to continue payment of benefits through the Post Office Card Account for the next five years.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","36900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518330","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>The number of JSA prison leavers by Work Programme attachment and job outcome from 2012, is published and available at:</p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-12T07:19:03.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518330/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518330/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Work Programme: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of offenders who joined the Work Programme on leaving prison secured a sustained job outcome within two years in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","36893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518331","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>Post Office Card Accounts provide a useful service to many people and there are no plans to change provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises, however, that working age claimants may also be receiving wages. As the account does not receive wages or allow for direct debit or standing order facilities, Post Office Card Accounts are not suitable for all of their needs. Those claimants are therefore being encouraged to open main stream bank accounts including credit union accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The Post Office Card Account contract was awarded from 01 December 2014 and expires on 30 November 2021 and there are no plans to amend that term.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","36900 ; 36901","2016-05-12T07:26:50.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518331/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518331/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Post Office Card Account","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to change provision of the Post Office Card Account.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","36899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518332","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>Post Office Card Accounts provide a useful service to many people and there are no plans to change provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises, however, that working age claimants may also be receiving wages. As the account does not receive wages or allow for direct debit or standing order facilities, Post Office Card Accounts are not suitable for all of their needs. Those claimants are therefore being encouraged to open main stream bank accounts including credit union accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The Post Office Card Account contract was awarded from 01 December 2014 and expires on 30 November 2021 and there are no plans to amend that term.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","36899 ; 36900","2016-05-12T07:26:50.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518332/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518332/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Post Office Card Account","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans that the Post Office Card Account will be available until 2021.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","36901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518333","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>There are currently 31 people employed at Westmorland House, whose working patterns equate to 26.48 whole time equivalents.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-12T07:15:28.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518333/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518333/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Jobcentres: Lytham St Annes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff are employed by Jobcentre Plus at Westmorland House, Lytham St. Annes.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","36890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518334","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department is in the process of reviewing all of its estates requirements as the current contract for most of the estate comes to an end in March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Commercial negotiations are underway at this time and consequently it is not appropriate to comment on any sites.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-12T07:19:17.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518334/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518334/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Jobcentres: Lytham St Annes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans his Department has to close or relocate Jobcentre Plus at Westmorland House, Lytham St. Annes.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","36891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518335","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>At the spending review, the Work and Health Unit secured £115m of funding, including at least £40m for a Work and Health innovation fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Work and Health Innovation Fund will trial new ways to help working age disabled people and people with health conditions get in, stay in, and return to work as well as benefit from improved health outcomes. This will include support for people with musculoskeletal conditions, including arthritis.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T14:45:13.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518335/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518335/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Health and Work Innovation Fund: Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of the Health and Work Innovation Fund his Department plans to allocate to programmes for people with arthritis.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","36756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518336","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>Access to Work does not record arthritis as a separate primary medical condition.</p><p> </p><p>Access to Work statistics, which include a breakdown of numbers helped by primary medical condition, are published quarterly here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/access-to-work-statistics-on-recipients--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/access-to-work-statistics-on-recipients--2</a>’</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T15:22:36.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518336/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518336/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Access to Work Programme: Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of Access to Work funding supports people with arthritis.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","36757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518338","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>2,144 people have been referred to Fit for Work with a musculoskeletal condition since the launch of the programme in March 2015.</p><p> </p><p>All statistical information has been provided by either HML or Scottish Government. It has not previously been published and is non-validated.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-11T14:45:58.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518338/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518338/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Fit for work scheme: Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in the Fit For Work scheme have a musculoskeletal condition.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","36758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518339","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-11","<p>Development of the Work and Health Programme design is well underway, including engagement with a wide range of stakeholders. The Department has commenced the commercial process for the programme by releasing the Prior Information Notice for potential providers on 28 April.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on what the information reporting requirements will be for people with a disability or health condition are yet to be made.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-11T15:12:27.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518339/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518339/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-09","Work and Health Programme: Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the Work and Health Programme meets the needs of people with arthritis.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","36759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518340","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not collect data on the number of specially adapted homes. However, the Department does collect data on the number of Disabled Facilities Grants completed annually in England. The latest data available from 2013-14 indicates 42,586 adaptations were provided.</p><p>The Government is committed to helping older and disabled people to live independently and safely in their own homes for as a long as possible. Since 2010 we have invested over one billion pounds (£1,005,000,000) into the Disabled Facilities Grant, providing around 250,000 adaptations for older and disabled people's homes in England.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-12T09:20:18.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518340/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518340/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-09","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many specially adapted homes for (a) disabled and (b) elderly people there were in (i) Sunderland, (ii) the North East and (iii) England in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","36780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518380","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-12","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to my hon Friend in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-12T12:16:59.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518380/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518380/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-09","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to support the electric car industry.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","905003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518448","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-12","<p>Department for Transport officials are engaging closely with colleagues in the Department for Energy and Climate Change and any decision regarding future airport capacity will take into account the Government’s obligations under the Climate Change Act.</p><p> </p><p>On 14 December 2015 the Secretary of State for Transport announced that the Government would undertake a package of further work, including on measures to mitigate carbon impacts and address sustainability concerns, particularly during construction. This further work will conclude by the summer.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-12T09:35:25.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518448/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-09","Climate Change: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the potential effect of airport expansion on the UK's climate change goals.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","904995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518529","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-12","<p>That the UK has deployed the world’s first commercial scale tidal stream turbine MCT SeaGen, a 1.2MW project.</p><p>The world’s first multi-turbine tidal stream array, MeyGen 1A, received £10m in DECC innovation funding and will be deployed in the UK this year.</p><p>We are looking at what more we can do to support these developing technologies.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-12T11:22:10.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518529/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518529/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-09","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assistance she plans to provide for the development of tidal stream power technology.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","905007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518569","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-12","<p>Hinkley Point C is a good deal for consumers – it will provide reliable energy at an affordable cost, powering nearly six million homes for around 60 years and creating more than 25,000 jobs.</p><p>Today nuclear provides around 16% of our electricity but these ageing plants won’t go on forever. Therefore the Government is committed to our policy of building new nuclear in the interest of energy security, decarbonisation and keeping costs down for the consumer.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-12T11:21:20.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518569/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518569/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-09","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make it her policy to renegotiate with EDF the strike  price for Hinkley Point C power station.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","905010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518570","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-12","<p>We want to see even more competition to keep energy costs down for businesses.</p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority has already published some suggestions such as requiring suppliers to publish tariffs online and making switching easier for businesses on auto-rollover contracts.</p><p>We are looking forward to the CMA’s final report and are committed to implementing their recommendations.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-12T11:21:46.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518570/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518570/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-09","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she plans to take to improve the effectiveness of the energy supply market for businesses.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","904996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517924","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false",,"<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has indicated that it will not be possible to answer this question within the usual time period. An answer is being prepared and will be provided as soon as it is available.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517924/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517924/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-06","Directors: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reason Companies House publishes the month and year of birth of company directors.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","36710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517925","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>As of 6 May 2016, 63 companies had not informed Companies House that they no longer have bearer shares.</p><p> </p><p>No action will be taken against these companies at the present time. There is no statutory obligation for any company that has converted bearer shares to registered shares to inform Companies House until it delivers its annual return or confirmation statement.</p><p> </p><p>I have requested the Registrar of Companies to write to the Hon Member with the list of the company names.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-11T15:58:05.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517925/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517925/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-06","Shares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 May 2016 to Question 35753, how many and which companies have not confirmed to Companies House that they no longer have bearer shares; and what action he plans to take against such companies.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517926","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The table below shows the countries and territories that have made requests to the UK for assistance in recovering criminal assets.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year Received</p></td><td><p>Requesting Country</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>Egypt</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Czech Republic</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>Iran</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Italy</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>Switzerland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cyprus</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Italy</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Brazil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Netherlands</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures only show countries where 6 or more requests have been made for restraint or confiscation. This is because disclosure of figures where 5 or fewer requests have been made may lead to the identification of an individual Mutual Legal Assistance request. Please note that these figures are taken from local management information, and have not been quality assured to the level of published National Statistics. As such they should be treated as provisional and therefore subject to change.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-05-12T10:21:46.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517926/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517926/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-06","Money Laundering: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which foreign countries made requests to the UK to recover criminal assets they had identified as having been laundered in the UK in each year since 2009; and how much in criminal assets was recovered from the UK for each of those countries in each such year.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517927","Home Office","false","2016-05-11","<p>As the Answer to Question 35790 set out, the Action Plan for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist finance states that there is no definitive measure of the scale of money laundering, but the best available international estimate, by the United Nations Office for Drugs and Crime (UNODC), of amounts laundered globally are equivalent to 2.7% of global GDP or US$1.6 trillion in 2009. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills does not hold data on criminal assets held abroad. Criminal assets recovered since 2009 under asset sharing arrangements were set out in the previous answer.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-05-11T11:58:18.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517927/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517927/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-06","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 3 May 2016 to Question 35790, what data her Department holds on criminal assets abroad and whether such assets are recovered or not.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517928","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Diverted Profits Tax is designed to counteract contrived arrangements used to avoid tax in the UK, and incentivise businesses to change their behaviour and pay tax on profits from economic activities in the UK. The Office for Budget Responsibility's (OBR) recent assessment at Budget 2016 is that overall yield (including Corporation Tax from behavioural change) is expected to be close to that originally scored.</p><p> </p><p>The OBR noted on page 122 of its “Economic and fiscal outlook” March 2016: “Our forecast assumes that overall yield from the measure will be close to that originally scored, but we now expect that around two-thirds of the yield will come through higher Corporation Tax payments (as firms restructure their tax affairs) rather than via the diverted profits tax itself.” This is available at: http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/March2016EFO.pdf.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-12T10:29:07.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517928/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517928/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-06","Taxation: Profits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was raised by the diverted profits tax in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517929","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>As far as I am aware there were no cases of this kind in the period 2009-10 to the present.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-12T09:37:01.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517929/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517929/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-06","Treasury: Legal Representation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for how many court and tribunal cases his Department did not send a legal representative in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517930","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation was established on 31st March 2016 however breaches of financial sanctions have previously been reported to HM Treasury. There are 441 records of alleged breaches reported to HM Treasury between September 2013 and December 2015. There are no records prior to September 2013.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not hold the requested information regarding HMRC's large business database.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not determine wrongdoing but works closely with UK law enforcement to deal with suspected breaches. It is a matter for law enforcement to make any referrals to the Crown Prosecution Service.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-11T13:07:17.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517930/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517930/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-06","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many reports of sanctions breaches were made to the Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation (OFSI) in each year since 2009-10; how many of those alleged breaches concerned businesses in HM Revenue and Customs' large business database; in how many such cases (a) the OFSI identified wrongdoing and (b) made a referral to the Crown Prosecution Service for prosecution in each such year.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","36721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517931","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is split into four sub-departments, or business areas, for delivery purposes, which are supported by corporate areas.</p><p> </p><p>Please see below the expenditure and full time equivalent (FTE) staff for each of those areas for the period 2009/10 onwards.</p><p> </p><p>Net expenditure (£m)</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>09/10</p></td><td><p>10/11</p></td><td><p>11/12</p></td><td><p>12/13</p></td><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>14/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Enforcement and Compliance</p></td><td><p>1,033</p></td><td><p>1,004</p></td><td><p>991</p></td><td><p>1,028</p></td><td><p>1,037</p></td><td><p>987</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Business Tax</p></td><td><p>222</p></td><td><p>248</p></td><td><p>181</p></td><td><p>185</p></td><td><p>156</p></td><td><p>201</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Personal Tax</p></td><td><p>763</p></td><td><p>682</p></td><td><p>726</p></td><td><p>728</p></td><td><p>670</p></td><td><p>531</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Benefits &amp; Credits</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>154</p></td><td><p>157</p></td><td><p>153</p></td><td><p>154</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Corporate</p></td><td><p>1,760</p></td><td><p>1,477</p></td><td><p>1,647</p></td><td><p>1,566</p></td><td><p>1,629</p></td><td><p>1,595</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMRC</p></td><td><p>3,947</p></td><td><p>3,575</p></td><td><p>3,699</p></td><td><p>3,664</p></td><td><p>3,645</p></td><td><p>3,468</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>HMRC has not yet published accounts for 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>FTE staff</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>09/10</p></td><td><p>10/11</p></td><td><p>11/12</p></td><td><p>12/13</p></td><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>15/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Enforcement and Compliance</p></td><td><p>26,864</p></td><td><p>25,475</p></td><td><p>25,334</p></td><td><p>26,601</p></td><td><p>26,923</p></td><td><p>26,2