"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517843","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research is funding a £1.5 million evaluation of the effectiveness, cost effectiveness and acceptability of dose adjustment strategies in antiepileptic drug management in pregnancy. The report of the evaluation is expected to be published in February 2017.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-11T15:58:20.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517843/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517843/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-05","Pregnancy: Epilepsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support he is providing for research into epilepsy medication for pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","36657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517844","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department has not conducted or commissioned any specific research on the health effects of male circumcision.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-11T15:59:02.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517844/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517844/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-05","Circumcision","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research his Department has conducted on the health benefits and risks of male circumcision.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","36675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517845","Department of Health","false","2016-05-11","<p>NHS England is in the process of re-considering its decision to remove pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) from the specialised commissioning annual prioritisation process. As such, no final decisions have yet been taken by NHS England as to whether or not they will routinely commission PrEP. This process, which is being overseen by NHS England’s Specialised Services Commissioning Committee, is expected to complete by the end of May 2016. Until the outcome of this process is known, NHS England will continue to work with Public Health England and the Department on planning for the proposed £2 million investment in an early implementer test site programme for PrEP. As part of this, NHS England will be exploring how, and where appropriate, a period of further support might be offered to the participants enrolled on the PROUD study. All the PROUD trial participants signed an explicit consent form that made clear that there was no long term commitment to continue providing PrEP beyond the trial.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","36687 ; 36688","2016-05-11T14:03:03.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517845/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517845/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-05","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the £2 million allocated by NHS England over the next two years to make pre-exposure prophylaxis available at early implementer test sites will be in addition to funding from the specialised commissioning budget.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","36686"
