"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517849","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The number of stop file entries changes continuously and we do not hold data on volumes of entries for specific days.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:24:52.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517849/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517849/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people were on the HM Passport Office stop file on 31 December (a) 2015, (b) 2014, (c) 2013, (d) 2012, (e) 2011, and (f) 2010.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517850","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office ran a Call for Information on the operation of the Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) regime between 25 February and 25 March 2015. We received more than 60 responses from a wide range of stakeholders, including law enforcement agencies, the financial sector, and the legal and accountancy sectors. Subsequently, further discussions were held with private and public sector bodies through a series of workshops.</p><p>The Government published the Action Plan for Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist finance on 21 April 2016. The Action Plan sets out the Government’s programme to deliver a significantly improved anti-money laundering regime for the UK. This includes the replacement of the SARs IT infrastructure. A summary of the submissions received following the Call for Information is set out in the Action Plan at Annex B.</p><p>In the Action Plan, we announced our commitment to develop a stronger public private partnership to tackle money laundering and the financing of terrorism, and as part of that we will engage with public and private stakeholders to develop the replacement.</p><p>The stakeholders will include law enforcement agencies, government departments, and businesses in the ‘regulated sector’ including banks, the legal and accountancy sectors, and estate agents. We will also include regulatory and supervisory bodies, and public bodies for whom SARs are of value.</p><p>This engagement will enable us to ensure that the replacement of the SARs IT architecture will deliver significant benefits for all of the sectors involved in the SARs regime. As we set out in the Action Plan, we will reform the SARs regime, making the necessary legislative, operational and technical changes, by October 2018.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","36671","2016-05-12T08:58:24.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517850/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517850/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Data Protection: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with which public and private sector stakeholders her Department has (a) engaged and (b) plans to engage in the implementation of the Government's proposed improvements to the SARs IT infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517851","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The number of detections over the last 6 years is provided in the table below. This data is drawn from management information and includes the detection of current and expired documents. We are continuing to invest in passport counter fraud techniques. For example, we are in the process on introducing new facial matching technology and new data analytics tools to enhance the security of our processes and support fraud investigations.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Fraudulently Obtained Genuine Document Detections</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p><strong>825</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p><strong>1,096</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p><strong>956</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p><strong>1,223</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p><strong>548</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p><strong>1,013</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:26:28.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517851/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517851/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Passports: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many fraudulently-obtained genuine passports HM Passport Office has detected in each year from 2010 to date.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517852","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>Entries are retained on the Her Majesty’s Passport Office Stop File for reasons of public protection and the prevention of crime.</p><p>Given the nature of the data, it would be inappropriate to disclose the volume of entries.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T09:56:11.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517852/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517852/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people are currently on the HM Passport Office stop file.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517853","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The team has a full time equivalent of 26 members of staff and amongst its responsibilities is to act as the single point of entry to Her Majesty’s Passport Office for law enforcement partners.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T10:00:48.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517853/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517853/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","HM Passport Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff are in the HM Passport Office team which acts as the single point of entry for law enforcement partners.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517854","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office ran a Call for Information on the operation of the Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) regime between 25 February and 25 March 2015. We received more than 60 responses from a wide range of stakeholders, including law enforcement agencies, the financial sector, and the legal and accountancy sectors. Subsequently, further discussions were held with private and public sector bodies through a series of workshops.</p><p>The Government published the Action Plan for Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist finance on 21 April 2016. The Action Plan sets out the Government’s programme to deliver a significantly improved anti-money laundering regime for the UK. This includes the replacement of the SARs IT infrastructure. A summary of the submissions received following the Call for Information is set out in the Action Plan at Annex B.</p><p>In the Action Plan, we announced our commitment to develop a stronger public private partnership to tackle money laundering and the financing of terrorism, and as part of that we will engage with public and private stakeholders to develop the replacement.</p><p>The stakeholders will include law enforcement agencies, government departments, and businesses in the ‘regulated sector’ including banks, the legal and accountancy sectors, and estate agents. We will also include regulatory and supervisory bodies, and public bodies for whom SARs are of value.</p><p>This engagement will enable us to ensure that the replacement of the SARs IT architecture will deliver significant benefits for all of the sectors involved in the SARs regime. As we set out in the Action Plan, we will reform the SARs regime, making the necessary legislative, operational and technical changes, by October 2018.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","36672","2016-05-12T08:58:24.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517854/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517854/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Data Protection: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she expects that the Government's proposed improvements to subject access request IT infrastructure will be completed.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","36671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517855","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>It is not possible to provide a full answer to this question. I shall write to the hon. Gentleman on the issues he has raised.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T11:39:28.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517855/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517855/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many children have been reunited with their families in the UK in (a) the last five years and (b) the last year under (i) the EU Dublin III Regulations, (ii) part 11 of the UK immigration rules, (iii) other parts of the UK immigration rules and (iv) under exceptional circumstances.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","36689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517856","Home Office","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Home Office has an internal target to consider all new Further Leave applications within six months of application. The resources in place in Complex Casework Directorate for Further Leave applications from failed asylum seekers granted Discretionary Leave to Remain is based around meeting this internal target. Our records indicate that the average time taken to decide such applications is 186 days.</p><p>Note: This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-12T09:57:39.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517856/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517856/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the Complex Casework Directorate resources to manage the application for renewal of asylum-related discretionary leave to remain; and what the average time taken is for such application renewals to be processed.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","36691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517857","Home Office","false","2016-05-10","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally. The issuance of Harassment Warning Notices, also known as Police Information Notices (PINs), is an operational matter for Chief Constables. Responsibility for the publication of information relating to PINs rests with Chief Constables.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-05-10T12:17:18.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517857/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517857/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-05","Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many harassment warnings each police force in England issued in the most recent financial year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","36661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517858","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>To determine the award of contracts, tenders are assessed against pre-defined and published evaluation criteria by an evaluation panel with relevant expertise. This assessment follows the EU Public Procurement principle of selecting the ‘most economically advantageous tender’. The evaluation has two main sections - technical evaluation and commercial evaluation.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T13:08:32.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517858/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517858/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-05","Developing Countries: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what criteria her Department uses to determine the award of contracts for projects overseas.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","36647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517859","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-11","<p>No additional weighting is given to bids made by British companies tendering for contracts for projects overseas.</p><p>100% of DFID aid assistance is untied. British companies have proven to be very successful, winning over 85% of contracts awarded by DFID and also competing successfully for contracts from other international development agencies.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-11T13:08:16.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517859/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517859/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-05","Developing Countries: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what weighting is given to bids made by British companies tendering for contracts from her Department for projects overseas.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","36648"
